          "guidance": "M1: Setting equal to zero may be implied by an attempt to solve the quadratic. A1: (do not accept 2.67 but $2.6\\dot{6}$ can be accepted.)"
        },
        {
          "label": "(b)",
          "marks": 3,
          "answer": "$x = \\frac{8}{3}$ is minimum, $x = -2$ is maximum",
          "markAllocation": [
            {
              "code": "M1",
              "type": "M",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Attempts to differentiate their $\\frac{\\text{d}y}{\\text{d}x}$ to achieve $\\frac{\\text{d}^2y}{\\text{d}x^2} = Cx + D$ where $C, D \\neq 0$."
            },
            {
              "code": "dM1",
              "type": "M",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Substitutes in one of their x values for part (a) into their $\\frac{\\text{d}^2y}{\\text{d}x^2}$ and draws a consistent conclusion with their value found."
            },
            {
              "code": "A1",
              "type": "A",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Correct second derivative, correct values for $\\frac{\\text{d}^2y}{\\text{d}x^2}$ at $x = \\frac{8}{3}, -2$ and draws a correct conclusion with reason for both."
            }
          ],
          "guidance": "M1: Allow if found in part (a). dM1: Accept with correct unsimplified values OR with correct reason, e.g. $\\frac{\\text{d}^2y}{\\text{d}x^2} < 0$ hence maximum, if no substitution seen. It is dependent on the previous method mark. Accept “concave down” for a maximum and “concave up” for a minimum. A1: Values need not be simplified but if simplified values seen they must be correct. It must be clear which point corresponds with each conclusion. NB Allow M1dM1A0 if no substitution is seen as long as reason is given, e.g. When x = −2, $\\frac{\\text{d}^2y}{\\text{d}x^2} < 0$ hence max. Alt (b) M1: Attempts to evaluate $\\frac{\\text{d}y}{\\text{d}x}$ both side of at least one of their stationary points. dM1: Evaluates $\\frac{\\text{d}y}{\\text{d}x}$ between their two stationary points and the other side of at least one of them, considers signs and draws a consistent conclusion. A1: Evaluates $\\frac{\\text{d}y}{\\text{d}x}$ correctly either side of both of their stationary points (three points required, you may need to check the evaluation) and draws correct conclusions for both. A method via calculus is required, so reasoning from the shape of a cubic scores no marks."
        }
      ]
    },
